# Commit convention

## When a feature is completed

1. Run `pnpm run test` and `pnpm run build` (if application code changed)
2. Update `docs/features/F*.md` (`status` → `done`)
3. Set matching `"status": "done"` in `scripts/github-tasks.manifest.json`
4. Merge PR to `main` with `Closes #<issue>` in the body (CI syncs issue state)
5. Update `docs/FEATURES.md` handoff log (and phase completion if applicable)
6. Commit with conventional format:

```
feat(scope): short description

- bullet points for notable changes
```

Scopes: `config`, `sync`, `backfill`, `dashboard`, `alerts`, `backup`, `docs`, `db`

## Branches and PRs

- Feature branches: `phase-<n>/<id>-<slug>` (e.g. `phase-3/f3-classification`)
- PRs target `main` and must include `Closes #N` for completed features
- See `.cursor/rules/github-workflow.mdc` for the full checklist

## Examples

```
feat(config): add app_config table and settings panel
feat(backfill): checkpoint-driven full backfill with gap detection
feat(dashboard): historical battery chart and period selector
feat(alerts): telegram battery SOC threshold notifications
feat(backup): db dump script and rclone google drive profile
docs: restructure features per-file, add INIT and BACKUP guides
```

## Do not

- Commit `.env`, `.env.local`, or backup dumps with secrets
- Mark a feature done without updating `docs/features/`, `github-tasks.manifest.json`, and a merged PR with `Closes #N`
- Mix unrelated features in one commit when they can be split logically
